dataset.title: Summary of plant community structure of thinleaf alder sites along the Tanana River floodplains from 2006.

para.literalLayout: This dataset contains a summary of plant species composition and abundance data from thinleaf alder sites along the Tanana River floodplains in 2006. This includes stem counts by species (or genus) for all woody plants >2m in height (both separated by dbh size class and combined), stem counts by species for all woody plants <2m in height, percent cover of each forb and graminoid species, mosses, and lichens, and percent of bare ground. The presence or absence of moose and snowshoe hare feces are also indicated.

While metadata will be freely available to those requesting it, the data manager will assure that any restrictions on access to data sets in the database will be enforced. Data will not be released without proper permission first being obtained from the investigator who generated the data.

Researchers should receive adequate acknowledgment for the use of their data by others and should be provided with copies of publications using their data. Users of data from the data base must be aware that data is not to be sold or redistributed.

It is considered a matter of professional ethics to acknowledge the work of other scientists. Thus, the Data User will properly cite the Data Set in any publications or in the metadata of any derived data products that were produced using the Data Set.

45 transects (50 m x 5 m) were established in alder-dominated stands representing a large range in alder stand structure and terrace heights. Each transect was subdivided into ten 5 m x 5 m plots. After initial vegetation sampling, multivariate analyses of community structure were conducted to aggregate plots of each transect into larger zones of homogenous vegetation that were then used for subsequent sampling. The aggregated plots from each transect are referred to as sites.

FIELD: Forty-five 50 x 5 m transects were established in thinleaf alder dominated stands running perpendicular to the Tanana River. Each transect was divided into ten 5 x 5 m plots. Within each 5 m x 5 m plot, the diameter at breast height (dbh) of all trees and shrubs > 2 m tall were measured. All woody plants < 2 m were counted in one 1 m x 1 m quadrat randomly placed within each plot. The percent cover of forbs (by species), graminoids (by species), mosses, and lichens in each quadrat were estimated. The presence or absence of moose and snowshoe hare feces within each quadrat were recorded. After initial vegetation sampling, multivariate analyses of community structure were conducted in order to aggregate plots from each transect into larger zones of homogeneous vegetation. The plots were grouped using detrended correspondence analysis (DCA), based on the size structure and stem density of thinleaf alder, willow, balsam poplar, and white spruce, and on the abundance of all other vegetation, classified by growth form (shrub, forb, graminoid, moss, and lichen). In the field, some of the aggregated plots were subdivided to account for physical heterogeneity, e.g. an abrupt rise in terrace height. These aggregated plots from each transect are referred to as sites (n = 89 sites). The data presented here are the site means of plot-level data.
